	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Signet Strategies: Frodo, Gandalf, and Theoden<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.79)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=18423'>Giorgio "°pen" Besagni</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=18423&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 29, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> The Frodo Signet <br />
<br />
Frodo, Son of Drogo<br />
The companion that embodies the Frodo signet is not a companion who sees much use. This is understandable up to a point, after all, the most commonly seen companions are those with universal applications. As a general rule, the more specific the game-text, the less it will see use. Frodo, Son of Drogo is no where near as universal as, for example, Frodo, Reluctant Adventurer or Frodo, Courteous Halfling (who, incidentally, has the Frodo signet as well), and therefore doesn’t get used as often. However, the text of Frodo, Son of Drogo is very useful if you allow for it and, in fact, the text can be one of the most powerful texts of any companion in the game. <br />
<br />
There are over 20 companions with the Frodo signet, including Legolas, Greenleaf, Boromir, Son of Denethor, Faramir, Son of Denethor, Merry, Learned Guide, Pippin, Woolly-headed Rascal, Sam, Resolute Half-ling and Aragorn, Elessar Telcontar, and every version of Smeagol that isn’t a ring-bearer. All of these characters see regular use, admittedly some more than others, and each of them can be used to help keep Frodo alive. The best options available are, of course, the discardable Hobbits. If Frodo gets injured, exert either Merry, Learned Guide or Pippin, Woolly-headed Rascal to heal him and then discard the Hobbit. Then, of course, play those hobbits again – an excellent way to soak up wounds for no ill effect. Also, with the three Gondor companions and Sam, you have a strong Fellowship with big fighters and two sacrificial lambs to help eat up all the wounds. <br />
<br />
Of course this does lead to the question of why all this is necessary. Most decks don’t run Frodo, Son of Drogo and having Frodo die from wounds is not exactly a common occurrence. But that’s not the point. The point is that using this version of Frodo allows you to use other cards that exert Frodo, and keep using those cards as much as you like (cards like Sting, Baggins Heirloom, The One Ring, The Binding Ring, Dear Friends, Halfling Deftness or A Marvel). Each of these cards is restricted in use because no companion has infinite vitality, but Frodo, Son of Drogo allows for multiple uses as you can keep healing him. In fact, there is no restriction on how many times you can heal him each turn, so theoretically you can use Sting, Baggins Heirloom 3 times every turn. Suddenly, Smeagol becomes a combat companion. His text also helps keep down your burden count as it allows Frodo to take more wounds before he has to start taking burdens to stay alive. In addition, this Smeagol/Frodo combination is strong against such heavy wounding shadow strategies that include the Twilight Witch-King or Ringwraith culture Orcs. <br />
<br />
Dear Friends<br />
Given that you are only allowed four copies of each card in your draw deck, any card that gets cards back form the discard pile and gives you the opportunity to use them again is a GOOD THING. This card goes one better than most such cards because it allows you to get any free peoples card you like, no restrictions. It gets even better if it’s used by a companion with the Frodo signet. For example, exert Merry, Learned Guide to get back two copies of, for example, Merry, Learned Guide. Place those cards on the bottom of your draw deck and use Sam, Frodo’s Gardener (who also, incidentally, has the Frodo signet) to shuffle your deck and improve your chances of getting one of those two copies sooner. Or how about using Dear Friends to get back a discardable Hobbit and another copy of Dear Friends? Keep the cycle going all game! <br />
<br />
Frodo’s Pipe<br />
And, just like in the Aragorn-signet article, we hit a snag in the theory about how great signets can be. For not only is this the worst Frodo-signet card in the game, it is also the worst Pipe in the game, and quite possibly the worst Possession. Not to mention a strong contender for worst card ever. To make this card worth using you are going to need at least 2 other pipes in play and have the pipeweed to use it. So, assuming 2 copies of each Pipe (otherwise you have no chance of drawing all the pipes each game) and 4 Pipeweeds in your deck, that’s already 10 cards devoted to it. Out of the five other pipes available to use, only 2 of them can be borne by other Hobbits. To use any of the other pipes you are forced to start including other cultures and this heavily dictates the nature of your deck. Also, remember that if you use Bilbo’s pipe you are going to have to start using tales to make it worth your while. On top of all this, if you don’t use companions with the Frodo signet, then Frodo’s Pipe is also going to be a bit of a waste of space. Gandalf’s Pipe has to be borne by Gandalf, forcing you to use the only Frodo-signet Gandalf there is. Gimli’s Pipe can only be borne by Gimli, again forcing your deck selection if you are going to get the most out of Frodo’s Pipe. In short, there will be very little room for anything else in your deck! But if you really like using Pipes, Pipeweed and specific companions, then you might as well use it. Be warned, though, the deck will be very weak and won’t be able to handle any Shadow strategy other than, possibly, burdens. <br />
<br />
Mind Your Own Affairs<br />
After the low of Frodo’s Pipe, we’re back to top form with this awesome card. When the original set first came out, Power According To His Stature was (and still is!) one of the most popular cards available. For one burden you get to wound every minion skirmishing the Ring-bearer – invaluable against swarm strategies, what’s not to like? And here we have a variant on the theme. Sure, it can only wound one minion but it can be used on any companion with the Frodo signet. This can be very effective if used correctly. Not only do we have the usual swarm protection that Power According To His Stature provides, but it can also be used in conjunction with other cards to give an instant kill. For example, try exhausting Shelob with Fourth Level, then assign her to Faramir, Son of Denethor and hit her with Mind Your Own Affairs. Or use Ithilien Trap on Castamir and have Boromir, Son of Denethor step up to the plate. Or have Gandalf, Friend of the Shirefolk with Shadowfax take on any vitality 2 minion and follow up with Mind Your Own Affairs. The possibilities are numerous, and remember, it’s still quality protection against minion swarms. Any direct wounding is always good, and this is better than most. <br />
<br />
No Use That Way<br />
This upgrade from Mind Your Own Affairs costs a painful three burdens to use. Still, I guarantee there will be times when you want it. Minion swarms are still as annoyingly popular as ever and Power According To His Stature and Mind Your Own Affairs are needed in multiple to help out. No Use That Way allows you to take out one of the minions with just one card. It can save many companions and, as such, must be seen as a good thing. Like Mind Your Own Affairs, it can be combined effectively with Gandalf, Friend of the Shirefolk and Shadowfax to let the wizard take out some of the bigger minions. It can also be used with other direct wounding such as Hobbit Sword-Play, various Gondor fortifications, and Orc-bane. Have Frodo, Son of Drogo bear Sting, Baggins Heirloom and play Orc-bane during the maneuver phase to wound three Orcs. Follow up with Mind Your Own Affairs and No Use That Way as needed, and then next turn use Frodo, Son of Drogo’s text to heal him. Wash, rinse, repeat! <br />
<br />
Straining Towards Us <br />
Removing twilight is always a good thing, and with this one card you can possibly remove 9! On average, if your deck has planned for it, you can remove 4 or 5 twilight every time you play this card. It makes double moving so much easier and, at the end of the day, what is this game if not a race to site 9? Moving fast is always a good thing, and this card helps. What’s more, it plays very well with the other Frodo signet cards, in particular Mind Your Own Affairs and No Use That Way. You can add burdens to kill off all the minions, remove any remaining twilight and then move again – all without risking losing a skirmish. Add in the benefits of Dear Friends to get back all those cards again, and you’re laughing all the way to site 9. <br />
<br />
A strong free peoples half of a deck based on the Frodo signet would, in my opinion, look something like this: <br />
<br />
Starting Fellowship: <br />
<br />
1 Frodo, Resolute Hobbit <br />
1 The One Ring, The Ruling Ring<br />
1 Merry, Friend To Sam<br />
1 Boromir, Son of Denethor <br />
<br />
Draw Deck: <br />
<br />
2 Aragorn, Elessar Telcontar <br />
2 Faramir, Son of Denethor <br />
2 Pippin, Guard of Minas Tirith <br />
1 Sam, Frodo’s Gardener<br />
4 Power According To His Stature <br />
4 Mind Your Own Affairs <br />
2 No Use That Way <br />
2 Straining Towards Us <br />
1 Sam’s Pack<br />
4 Hobbit Sword <br />
3 Knight’s Spear <br />
2 Might of Numenor <br />
4 Extraordinary Resilience <br />
<br />
These 35 cards provide a strong base of companions with decent strengths and the direct wounding cards allow you to breeze past most shadow strategies. The main drawback of this deck is that it quickly accumulates burdens and gets shutdown to a crawl when facing a shadow burden strategy. To that end, burden defense in the shape of Extraordinary Resilience has been included. Combined with a shadow strategy that cycles cards at a reasonable rate, this Free Peoples strategy can be a severe pain for most opponents. The only other problem is that the deck is fairly rare intensive. <br />
<br />
So what about a non-rare Frodo signet deck? Well how about this… <br />
<br />
Starting Fellowship: <br />
<br />
1 Frodo, Son of Drogo<br />
1 The One Ring, The Ruling Ring<br />
1 Merry, Learned Guide<br />
1 Faramir, Son of Denethor <br />
<br />
Draw Deck: <br />
<br />
3 Merry, Learned Guide <br />
4 Pippin, Woolly-headed Rascal <br />
2 Boromir, Son of Denethor <br />
2 Arwen, Elven Rider <br />
2 Sam, Frodo’s Gardener <br />
3 Knocked On The Head <br />
3 Warmed Up A Bit <br />
3 Dear Friends <br />
2 Straining Towards Us <br />
2 Hobbit Sword <br />
2 Gondorian Sword <br />
<br />
Down to 30 cards this time, and a completely different feel. Whereas the previous strategy was to step up to all the nasty minions, this time you want to avoid them. Assign Merry and Pippin to the biggest threats each time, and then discard them. With the multiple copies and the Dear Friends you should easily be able to play them again next turn and do the same again. Straining Towards Us is an optional extra in this deck as you won’t be double moving that often, so feel free to replace them with some cards of your choice. But beyond that, this is the best option you can take for guaranteeing survival. Although this deck has lost, it has never (as far as I’ve seen) done so by having the Ring-bearer getting killed off. Combine this with a stopping shadow side and you’ll have an interesting game. <br />
<br />
The Gandalf Signet <br />
<br />
Gandalf, The Grey Wizard<br />
The companion that embodies the Gandalf signet, The Grey Wizard, is not the normal choice you’d see in a Gandalf-based deck (especially these days when there are stronger, more combat orientated choices available). But, like Frodo, Son of Drogo, if you plan for The Grey Wizard he can be excessively powerful. What The Grey Wizard provides is an effective exertion for 2 twilight. This is a very good deal and one that can help a lot. Although the recent Gandalf culture cards tend to thrive on copious twilight, the early sets provided Gandalf with a way of avoiding a lot of twilight. If used today, this twilight removal can be all the more effective due to its unexpectedness. Stock nothing but Gandalf signet characters and with the exception of the Gondor gentlemen and possibly 2 Rohan men, every one of your companions will come out for 0 twilight. Combine this with other twilight reducing cards such as Gandalf’s Wisdom (discussed later), Let Folly Be Our Cloak and the original Gandalf’s Staff, and you can play out a lot of cards every turn for effectively no twilight. If The Grey Wizard bears Gandalf’s Staff, you can exert him to play Arwen, Fair Elf Maiden and play Strength of Spirit to get Arwen out for no twilight and no exertion! In a deck based on the Gandalf signet, where copious twilight is not an issue, The Grey Wizard is easily the best option available. <br />
<br />
Gandalf’s Wisdom<br />
A Gandalf deck that avoids lots of twilight is not only possible, as we have just seen, but also strategically advantageous - any deck that avoids generating lots of twilight is. Gandalf’s Wisdom helps with this. Each copy applies to all possessions and artifacts played on a Gandalf signet card, and it is cumulative with other copies. So, just two copies of Gandalf’s Wisdom in play means that any possession or artifact played on a Gandalf signet companion now comes out for 0 twilight. In fact, combine this card with The Grey Wizard and you can play lots of cards every Fellowship phase and generate no twilight. And what little twilight is generated (i.e. by conditions) can be eaten away by Let Folly Be Our Cloak. What more can you ask for? <br />
<br />
Trust Me As You Once Did<br />
And so we arrive at a card that is so strong that it has given its name to an entire deck strategy. For one exertion you can give a companion a strength boost of up to 3. And with multiple copies out, you can keep doing it. Use Strength of Spirit to keep your Gandalf exertions going, use Narya and Gandalf’s Staff to increase Gandalf’s vitality, use multiple copies of Gandalf to keep healing him every turn … you can keep it going all game. The only real danger is if you’re hit with condition removal, but that’s what multiple copies are for. As I said, this is a card powerful enough to base an entire deck around, and it’s a strategy that is as popular and powerful today as it has ever been. <br />
<br />
Keep Your Forked Tongue<br />
As we’ve just seen, Trust Me As You Once Did is a card powerful enough to base an entire deck on. However, it does have its weak spots. Along with condition removal, the other main problem is the steady increase of exertion wound on Gandalf. Sooner or later you’re going to run out of vitality. And that eventuality will arrive even sooner if Gandalf starts taking wounds from skirmishes. So any wound prevention is even more important than normal. Send Gandalf bearing Glamdring up against the Cave Troll and you may indeed lose the skirmish, but play Keep Your Forked Tongue and there are no ill effects for doing so. It is a helpful card against most minions, but even better when skirmishing minions with damage bonuses. But there’s more. Red Wrath has seen an increase in tournament play recently, as has Whirling Strike. A well timed one-two with these cards can kill off a fully healthy Boromir. One well timed Keep Your Forked Tongue can see that this never happens. While Keep Your Forked Tongue is not as powerful as Trust Me As You Once Did and will never have a deck built around it, its defensive capabilities cannot be overstated; it’s an essential card for any Gandalf signet based deck. <br />
<br />
Down From The Hills<br />
Easily one of the most aggressive Free Peoples events in the game, and one of the most expensive. But the trick with this card is in realizing that you shouldn’t play this card to gain all the benefits at once. After all, making a character unable to take wounds does not (baring directed archery or other direct wounding) gel with making a character damage +2. Preventing wounds is a defense against losing a skirmish, damage +2 is for when you win one. So, this card actually has multiple uses. It is used to help win skirmishes and to minimize damage from a lost skirmish. The trick is in knowing when to use it for each use. <br />
<br />
The first option is to use Down From The Hills defensively against a swarm. Making an already strong character defender +1 and strength +5 lets him or her take on two big minions and take no wounds for losing it. Make Gandalf strength +5 and, even if he isn’t bearing any permanent strength boosters, he can now take on two minions of total strength 23 or less – and take no wounds because of it. Let him take on the Cave Troll and The Troll’s Keyward and he survives with no wounds. The second option is to use Down From The Hills defensively against a large minion. Make Aragorn strength +5 and unable to take wounds, and you effectively allow him to survive a direct confrontation with Sauron himself – with no wounds. The third option is to use Down From The Hills offensively against two medium sized minions. If Aragorn bears a weapon to make him a base strength of 10, then using Down From The Hills allows him to take on two minions totaling 14 strength (or less) without a care in the world. Add in another strength boost or two and he could get up to 20 or more strength. Suddenly your opponent’s big minions no longer look quite so scary. The fourth option is to use Down From The Hills offensively against one big-ish minion. Strength +5 and damage +2 is a fantastic bonus by any standards. It allows any companion to become a force to be reckoned with, while making the bigger companions even worse. Try using it on Aragorn with a sword as he faces The Witch-King. The weapon he bears may already make him damage +1, so now that he is damage +3, he kills The Witch-King in one hit. What’s not to like? <br />
<br />
Of course, any card with such versatility and power must be costed accordingly, and it is here that we encounter the big draw back of Down From The Hills. Exerting Gandalf three times is not something to be done lightly, and certainly not something that can be done often. Increasing his vitality (as discussed earlier when talking about Trust Me As You Once Did) can help, as can Strength of Spirit. But even with all this help, exerting Gandalf three times is still not something that can be done often. You need to time it for when you need it. It can help you survive against large odds and it can help you clear the playing field for a double move. But using it just because, or even just to get it out of your hand, is not advised. The excess pain caused to Gandalf will prove to be far worse in the long run. Still, played correctly, this is one of the best events in the game. <br />
<br />
Let Us Not Tarry<br />
Trust Me As You Once Did has a limit of +3 strength with each use. Let Us Not Tarry instantly gains an advantage in that it has no such draw back. For one exertion you can reduce a minion’s strength by up to 9, although usually it will be by 4 or 5. But even so, the mere potential of up to 9 is a very strong one. However, the big disadvantage Let Us Not Tarry is that it cannot be used to help Ring-bound companions. Therefore it cannot help out Frodo, or any other Ring-bearer and, as the entire game is about keeping the Ring-bearer alive, this is not that helpful. But it does allow you to keep other companions alive, and of course their continued existence helps keep the Ring-bearer alive - hopefully. But Let Us Not Tarry’s inability to directly help the Ring-bearer is a huge disadvantage and can prove costly if you have no other help for the Ring-bearer at a time when you need it. As such, Let Us Not Tarry should not be looked upon as an alternative for Trust Me As You Once Did, but as an addition. It can also be used should your opponent be inconsiderate enough to discard the copies of Trust Me As You Once Did that you have in play. It can also be used if there is more than a 3 point difference in strengths between your companion and its foe. Assuming you have 6 companions all with the Gandalf signet in play, then for one exertion you effectively get double the aid you’d get from one use of Trust Me As You Once Did. <br />
<br />
A strong Free Peoples half of a deck based on the Gandalf signet would, in my opinion, look something like this: <br />
<br />
Starting Fellowship: <br />
<br />
1 Frodo, Wicked Master <br />
1 The One Ring, The Ruling Ring<br />
1 Merry, Rohirrim Squire<br />
1 Pippin, Sworn To Service<br />
1 Sam, Great Elf Warrior <br />
<br />
Draw Deck: <br />
<br />
4 Gandalf, Defender of The West <br />
1 Theoden, King of The Golden Hall<br />
1 Eowyn, Daughter of Eomund<br />
1 Eomer, Keeper of Oaths<br />
2 Radagast, The Brown <br />
2 Wizard Staff <br />
1 Glamding, Lightning Brand<br />
4 Hobbit Sword <br />
3 Sword of Rohan <br />
4 Strength of Spirit <br />
4 Trust Me As You Once Did <br />
<br />
These 30 cards rely heavily on Trust Me As You Once Did and have no other Gandalf signet-based cards. But such is the way with Trust Me As You Once Did decks. Gandalf’s text requires him to be able to spot 3 companions of the same culture to keep his higher than normal strength. Thus, starting with 4 Hobbits allows him to keep his strength the instant he enters play. And the four Hobbits themselves are decent enough in a fight, with Sam starting on strength 7! If you bear in mind that the whole point of the deck is Trust Me As You Once Did, then the rest of it falls neatly into place as you focus on keeping Gandalf alive with plenty of vitality in order to use his exertions as much as much as possible. <br />
<br />
However, if you want a deck that uses more Gandalf signet based cards, try something like this: <br />
<br />
Starting Fellowship: <br />
<br />
1 Frodo, Wicked Master<br />
1 The One Ring, The Ruling Ring<br />
1 Merry, Rohirrim Squire<br />
1 Pippin, Sworn To Service<br />
1 Faramir, Ithilien Ranger <br />
<br />
Draw Deck: <br />
<br />
4 Gandalf, The Grey Wizard <br />
2 Aragorn, Driven By Need <br />
2 Boromir, Defender of Minas Tirith <br />
2 Sam, Samwise The Brave <br />
4 Hobbit Sword <br />
3 Gondorian Sword <br />
1 Gandalf’s Staff<br />
1 Narya<br />
3 Strength of Spirit <br />
4 Trust Me As You Once Did <br />
2 Keep Your Forked Tongue <br />
2 Let Us Not Tarry <br />
2 On Your Doorstep <br />
<br />
These 35 cards use more Gandalf signet-based cards, making for more variety, but the side-effect is an increased risk should Gandalf die. If he dies whilst using this deck, then potentially 8 cards become useless and all your future companions will cost more twilight. So wound prevention is an absolute must, and you have to time it correctly. Don’t bother using it to save Merry’s life if Gandalf is also assigned to a skirmish. You never know when Gandalf is going to need it. The importance of Gandalf to this deck cannot be overstated. Beyond that, it’s a traditional Gandalf signet deck utilizing Trust Me As You Once Did. Your opponent will have seen similar decks before, so the thing to bear in mind is that they’ll know how to counter it. Therefore, expect your copies of Trust Me As You Once Did to get discarded fairly quickly. But that’s where On Your Doorstep comes into play; just retrieve the copies that are discarded. <br />
<br />
The Theoden Signet <br />
<br />
Unlike the other signets, the Theoden signet has no signature companion whose text relates to other companions with the same signet. So, the first decision to be made is which version of Theoden to use. The two options are Theoden, Lord of The Mark and Theoden, Leader of Spears. Both their texts relate to other Rohan companions, so if the primary focus of your deck isn’t other Rohan companions, then it’s best to choose Leader of Spears as he has the better stats. In fact, so much better is Leader of Spears’ 3 vitality over Lord of The Mark’s 2, that unless you plan on playing lots of Rohan possessions on lots of Rohan companions, I’d suggest always using Leader of Spears regardless of the rest of your deck. So, now that that is sorted, let’s have a look at the cards that actually do relate to the Theoden signet. <br />
<br />
Forth Eorlingas!<br />
Ah, the joys of defender +1. Thinning the horde, allowing a strong companion to take on two medium minions, allowing a weak companion to sacrifice himself nobly for the cause against two of the strongest minions in existence – the possibilities are endless. And all this for just one exertion from Theoden. Er, an exertion? Maybe that’s not quite so good. Elendil’s Valor makes any Gondor companion defender +1 for no exertion and no twilight. Wielder of The Flame just requires you to spot Gandalf. Requiring an exertion can be a heavy cost, but the advantage Forth Eorlingas! has over Elendil’s Valor is a cross-cultural. Elendil’s Valor only works on Gondor companions, Forth Eorlingas! works on any companion regardless of their culture, provided they have the right signet. The advantage Forth Eorlingas! has over Wielder of The Flame is that Wielder of The Flame has an inbuilt way of being prevented, Forth Eorlingas! doesn’t. Once you’ve played it, that’s it. So, you have to ask yourself if you think the tradeoff is worth it. Personally, I think it is. An exertion is always a hard cost to pay, particularly as Rohan has no ready way to heal, but the advantages of a well timed defender +1 far outweigh the negatives. Remember, when you move to site 9 your opponent can see how many companions you have in play and will play his minions out accordingly. If you have a surprise defender +1 waiting in your hand, it can single-handedly win you the game. <br />
<br />
I Am Here<br />
Two exertions? Well that rules out using Lord of The Mark without giving him Herugrim. Looks like the decision about which Theoden to use has been made after all. Healing several companions twice is a fantastic ability, but the snag is how to then heal Theoden. 3 out of the 4 Theoden signet cards require you to exert Thedoen, and this one requires you to exert him twice. Without healing Theoden himself, you are limited to how many of these cards you can use. I Am Here worsens the problem because it hurts him even more than normal, but once again the benefits outweighs the cost. If you plan for Theoden to be exerting as much as possible in any one game, then you must make sure he never faces a minion unless he absolutely has to. Using multiple copies of Theoden in your deck allows you to use the spares to heal him, and assuming you’re going to be including either the Gondor or Gandalf cultures in your deck to maximize the benefits of the Theoden signet, you can also include Might of Numenor or Have Patience to heal him too. If planned for, I Am Here can be a game winner in that it keeps all your companions around that much longer. <br />
<br />
No Living Man<br />
In case you hadn’t noticed, the Rohan culture thrives on exerting minions and then taking advantage of the newly wounded minions. Elite Rider gets a +2 strength boost when skirmishing a wounded minion, Fey He Seemed gives a bigger bonus when used against a wounded minion, and Ever The Hope of Men can discard them. So, No Living Man gives you another way to exert some minions, except, Rohan doesn’t really need it. They have their various mounts, they have Rohirrim Bow, Valleys of The Mark, Merry’s Sword…the list goes on. Do they really need another? No. But a distinguishing factor of signet decks is that it tends to encompass more than one culture. So whilst Rohan may not need any more ways to exert minions, there remains the possibility that other cultures can make use of it. With various direct-wounding-during-a-skirmish abilities available, it is more than possible for No Living Man to be used effectively in various combos. For example, if Frodo has for some reason been confronted by the Cave Troll, then No Living Man can exhaust that nasty troll and Power According To His Stature can finish him off. Likewise for Boromir bearing Blade of Gondor while confronted by an Uruk-Hai or Orc. Also, it works great as an anti-swarm card. Exhaust all the minions you’re confronted by and then finish them off with Power According To His Stature. Alternately, exert multiple minions and follow up with multiple several copies of Unheeded. Or, to really annoy your opponent, play out Blades Drawn and sit there smugly. <br />
<br />
A strong Free Peoples half of a deck based on the Theoden signet would, in my opinion, look something like this: <br />
<br />
Starting Fellowship: <br />
<br />
1 Frodo, Hope of Free Peoples <br />
1 The One Ring, The Ruling Ring<br />
1 Eowyn, Dernhelm<br />
1 Eomer, Valiant Warchief<br />
Draw Deck: <br />
<br />
4 Theoden, Leader of Spears <br />
2 Aragorn, Defender of Free Peoples <br />
2 Faramir, Stout Captain <br />
1 Vorondil<br />
1 Merry, Swordthain<br />
1 Sam, Son of Hamfast<br />
3 Hobbit Sword <br />
3 Gondorian Sword <br />
2 Herugrim <br />
2 Long Spear <br />
3 Might of Numenor <br />
2 Noble Intentions <br />
4 Forth Eorlingas! <br />
3 I Am Here! <br />
<br />
These 35 cards contain most of the best fighters in the game whilst making full use of the Theoden signet’s ability to take on many foes at once and still keep going. Obviously, Theoden is very important to this deck and as such should not be unduly risked. He can heal 5 of the companions (twice each) three times. As such it’s those 5 who should be doing most of the fighting. OK, maybe not Merry, he’s in there for you to make him as high a ‘defender +X’ bonus as you can before sacrificing him in one fell swoop. But as Theoden is going to be doing a lot of exerting, the Might of Numenors are in there to heal him. Resist the temptation to use them to heal others – that’s what I Am Here is for. <br />
